2. Elementary Theory of Linear Operators

Definition of an operator. Operations with operators. Commutator, anticommutator. Kernel of an operator.
Eigenfunctions and eigenvalues. Degeneracy.
Linear, complex conjugate, inverse, transpose, Hermitian-conjugate and self-adjoint (Hermitian) operators.
Properties of operators:

properties of eigenvalues of linear self-adjoint operators;
properties of eigenfunctions of linear self-adjoint operators;
superposition principle;
completeness of eigenfunction systems;
eigenfunctions of commuting operators;
simultaneous measurement of physical observables.

Lecture 3. Types of Chemical Bonding in Crystals. Crystal Defects

General characteristics of chemical bonding in solids:

ionic bonding;
covalent bonding;
metallic bonding;
molecular (van der Waals) bonding;
hydrogen bonding.

Crystal defects:

point defects: Frenkel and Schottky defects;
line defects (dislocations);
surface defects;
volume defects.

Lecture 9. Electrical Conductivity of Metals. Ohm’s Law

Basic concepts of the classical theory of electrical conductivity in metals.
Boltzmann equation in the relaxation-time approximation.
Ohm’s law and its analysis.
Comparison of experimental and theoretical results:

Bloch–Grüneisen law;
electron–phonon and electron–electron scattering; Matthiessen’s rule;
Kondo effect;
electron–magnon scattering.

Lecture 3. Phase Space. Distribution Function

Phase space concept. Ensemble and time averages. Distribution function over microstates. Ergodic and quasi-ergodic hypotheses.
Liouville theorem. Properties of the distribution function.
Features of quantum systems:

wave–particle duality;
discreteness of physical observables;
indistinguishability of particles, spin, Pauli exclusion principle;
Heisenberg uncertainty relations;
statistical weight (thermodynamic probability), degeneracy.
